children.subject: With the utmost respect Ishaan, it's categorically unreasonable to expect the current classes to expand to have over more seats. In what I would consider an optimistic scenario, Data 100 would add 500 seats, 162 adds 100, 170 adds 300, 186 adds 300, 188 adds 400, and 189 adds 300. [Numbers are emotionally inspired by looking at Fall and Spring sizes of these courses]. That's 1900 seats, which still leaves us missing over a 1000 seats compared to last Spring. And if they add as many seats as I'm guessing, we're looking at the largest offering of Data 100 in history and possibly the same for some of the other courses.

Im not so sure, it seems like every semester every course is always underenrolled and then expand to meet more needs. I dont think I've ever been a part of CS/EECS course with a sizeable waitlist that didnt take in people from the waitlist without expanding at some point. I feel like this post would be more apt to revisit around phase 2, when we know more about the true enrollment numbers. Right now, whats being compared is previous semesters complete enrollment, and enrollment for next semester before things like expansions due to capacity. I still think itll be under, but I think it might be more like 500-1000 fewer seats than anything else. I mean looking at fall 2020, I'm almost positive the enrollment numbers will be higher next semester than this one if courses expand as they typically do. Also as stated before, a few popular courses are not being offered right now (presumably due to lack of people willing to teach them right now), and that maybe skews it. Sometimes professors teach courses under EE/EECS/INFO/etc instead of CS or teach their grad courses instead. Popularity is a factor (like 189 is suuuper popular in spring as opposed to fall). Maybe a more apt comparison would be enrollment numbers from before phase 1 of spring 2020 and fall 2020 vs now (if he already did this im sorry! I couldnt see it looking at the numbers). But yea, I wouldnt really call this a problem unless the same trend exists a couple weeks from now. Lastly, falls numbers might be down so much because of COVID? Not so sure about that one. Other opinions would be nice.

I'm pretty sure some/most all of these classes will expand as budgets are finalised and staff is hired. For example, I'm 99% certain Data 100 will have well over 1000 seats, compared to the 744 that are currently listed. It wouldn't surprise me if that's the case for other classes too
Yup, that or you're a senior with a very early Phase 1. It also consistently has few (<100) seats, which is practically neglibible when summed with all the other upper divs
Sorry to bring up an old post but what’s the reason 160 is so popular?

Don't know if it's particularly popular, probably on the same level as a 161 or 168, problem is it's constrained to a much smaller class size due to the design of the class. Most cs classes have hundreds of seats, but as beaker said above 160 usually has <100

history.content:
AFAIK, this is because of how teaching loads at universities work. We as students can expect to get a certain number of classes per year, but we don't get to choose what they are. It seems like the professors who normally teach systems classes don't want to teach at all next semester or are more interested in teaching graduate students.

The bulk of the loss seems to come from 160, 161, 169A, and 168 not being run. But unfortunately, if no professor wants to come up to the plate and teach these classes, there's no way for the department to force anyone to do it. The department heads don't have the ability to go RISELab and say "OK y'all are drawing straws and whoever gets the shortest one is going to have to teach 161 this semester". But there's your reason. The systems professors don't want to teach undergrads this semester. And if that's the case, there's very little that the department admin can really do about it besides maybe some pestering.

The upside I guess is that this is why adjuncts exist. To fill in these gaps. But the EECS department doesn't make heavy use of adjuncts so I don't know that's a route they're planning to go with at all.

spring confirmed online -> less kids enrolling in spring -> university won't be able to steal make as much money off us  -> therefore they hire less TAs and have to restrict enrollment to compensate
Yes, there is talk in the department in trying to fundamentally restructure the computer science major since the scaling right now is not sustainable.

+1, the department should do something about this (accept less students into Cal or hire more faculty). It's not reasonable to have thousands of students who have to play the lottery to get into overcrowded courses when there is a seat shortage. Other comparable schools have a far more reasonable number of computer science students by not over-accepting - we're probably the only school in the nation that has class sizes over 2000+ for intro courses and 700+ for some upper divs.
Unfortunately a lot of that is up to the Colleges and the University

@anon gear 2

1. EECS already has a tool to do this. It's called the GPA cap. If they truly wanted fewer students in CS, they could raise it to 3.7 or something. Or if they wanted to just relieve the teaching burden, they could make it such that you need a 3.3 in 61AB and 70 each. That way, 61B and 70 will be a lot smaller since if you didn't get a B+ or better in 61A, you would have little reason to take the follow-on classes.

2. It's not "playing the lottery" if it's skill. You don't get accepted by the school as intended CS and get a lottery number to determine whether or not you're in the major. And if you think that grades are too noisy to determine skill and that it's too nerve-wracking to have your major being in limbo, they have a provision for that too called the EECS major.

I don't understand all the complaints about the current system is broken or that there are too many students declaring CS. If there are too many CS majors, raise the cap. If you don't want to get judged after you get into the school, you have the option of having that judgement done by the freshmen admissions board.

I feel like LSCS existing is already way more of a provision for students than most other universities in the US. At most other US universities, deciding to do CS later will cost you a transfer of college and much more agonizing pain than declaring a major. Berkeley's problems stem from the fact that they run LSCS as a charitable service for students.

Say you went to CMU as a math major and later decided that you wanted to be CS. Well, then you have to deal with CMU's notoriously finicky and black-boxed internal SCS transfer, which is much less transparent than just the GPA cutoff.

history.content: <md>Folks are trying to work on communicating this, but I don't know about exact timelines. The short answer is, everyone is aware this is a massive challenge, and no one is happy about it. But, enrollments are largely determined by budgets allocated from campus. </md>

Hi,

Can a faculty or staff member please share some of the reasoning behind class offerings and course sizes for Spring 2021?  Some back of the envelope calculations show that Spring 2021 will have almost 3000 fewer seats than what was offered in Spring 2020, and almost 1500 fewer seats than Fall 2020.

I am hoping classes will expand as they often have in past semesters, but it feels unreasonable to expect the department to almost double the number of seats. 

I'm not sure if it's just me, but it also feels like there are way fewer class options  for Spring 2021 than there have been in the past. Almost no 16x classes are being offered, and certainly not the classes typically considered most accessible in our department (160, full 169 offering, etc). The current offerings seem to be catering to a very specific subset of students and don't meet the needs of the majority of students in our department. And there aren't enough seats to begin with.

My rough calculations are below using classes listed here and referencing class sizes as listed on Berkeley Guide. Strictly looking at CS upper division offerings; if I'm missing something please let me know. This math is a little generous because it includes 169L (which has 169A as a pre-req) AND 194-035, which isn't yet approved to be a CS upper div.
history.subject: Why are there ~3,000 fewer seats in CS upper divs for Spring 2021?
